<DOC><DOCNO> AP890724-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1345EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Storms     07-24 0223</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Storms,0231</SECOND><HEAD>Downpours in Western India Kill at Least 100</HEAD><DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Torrential downpours in western India onMonday triggered flash floods and landslides that collapsed houses,and one report said at least 100 people had died.   The deaths were reported by the United News of India news agencyin coastal Maharashtra state after the rain flooded rivers and highwinds knocked down houses and trees.   At least 13 people died in Bombay, the state capital, accordingto police.   An official at Bombay's meterological office said 11 inches ofrain was recorded in 24 hours. It is the highest figure recorded inone day since July 2, 1984, when 22 inches of rain fell.   The rain was accompanied by winds gusting up to 52 mph, theofficial said.   Bus and train services in the city were suspended and roads wereinundated with waist-deep water. Trucks were stranded in swirlingwaters and several villages were cut off, police said.   Transactions at the stock exchange, India's largest, weresuspended, said M.R. Mayya, an exchange official.   The army was called out in the districts of Beed, Deglur andBiloli to rescue the residents of 46 villages that had beensurrounded by floodwaters.   At least 2,400 fishermen were reported missing after they werecaught on the seas during the storm, the news agency said.</TEXT></DOC>